<TEXT>
the us cotton stockpile is outgrowing demand 
from domestic textile mills as well as from overseas markets 
according to an agriculture department report 
cotton exports in 198889 are forecast at 69 million bales down 
from 762 million bales last year 
aggressive pricing by major foreign exporters and heavy 
movement of us cotton under government price support loan have 
been largely responsible for the decline the report said monday 
when a farmer obtains a price support loan for cotton or another 
commodity it cannot be sold until the loan is repaid often when 
market prices are low a farmer will not repay the loan and forfeit 
the commodity to the government 
despite a number of adjustments in the loan program to make us 
cotton more competitive in the world market prices still remain 
above those of foreign competitors the report said 
meanwhile cotton use by us textile mills reached 76 million 
bales in 198788 the most in 15 years but this seasons mill use 
is expected to drop to 69 million bales 
reduced denim demand and consumer preference for more 
finecount yarn products are lowering mill use the report said 
as a result us cotton stockpiles which were less than 58 
million bales last aug 1 are expected to climb to 92 million by 
this aug 1 the beginning of the 198990 cotton marketing year 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

