<TEXT>
president bushs fastpaced asian trip provided 
a daily dose of telegenic photo opportunities but few clues about 
his brand of foreign policy other than that it will tone down 
americas approach on human rights 
it seemed bushs purpose in more than 18000 miles of travel was 
simply to touch base with other leaders and reaffirm friendly 
relations 
there was no sign of any new initiatives 
over five days bush zipped through tokyo beijing and seoul 
pumping hands and posing for pictures with more than 20 foreign 
leaders in dramatic settings 
the only time bush stood still was during a threehour appearance 
at the funeral of emperor hirohito 
not everything came off quite as planned the white house script 
did not call for the trip to vie for attention with the drama at 
home over john towers troubled nomination as secretary of defense 
and there was a diplomatic slap in beijing where chinese 
authorities prevented the countrys top dissident from attending 
bushs banquet 
at the very moment that bush was declaring the chineseamerican 
relationship vital to the security interests of the united states 
and was toasting the future of uschina relations a future 
filled with achievement good fortune and peace the chinese were 
taking a step that they must have known would be seen as insulting 
but the next day bush restricted himself to a muted expression of 
regret regret not outrage over the chinese refusal to let 
fang lizhi meet with him 
to rub it in the chinese through their foreign ministry 
spokesman gave bush a public lecture on human rights telling him 
in effect not to raise the subject 
human rights was not discussed white house press secretary 
marlin fitzwater reported later a day later fitzwater reversed 
himself and said human rights were discussed privately in china by 
bush but he couldnt say with whom 
fitzwater said bush believes that quiet diplomacy is the 
appropriate course for raising human rights in china 
that was a sharp contrast with former president ronald reagan 
who highlighted human rights problems in communist nations and 
always made the subject the very first topic of discussion in 
dealings with the soviet union 
right from the outset bush was thrown on the defensive in tokyo 
about tower 
world leaders who were ushered in for 20minute meetings with the 
new american president saw him peppered with embarrassing questions 
about the man he wants to run the pentagon 
the tower issue followed bush to beijing to seoul and back to 
washington where today the president was calling senators in 
onebyone to ask for their support 
for all of bushs activity in asia there was no sign of progress 
on nagging trade frictions particularly with japan and south korea 
members of south koreas national assembly applauded warmly when 
bush pledged not to remove the 42000 american troops in that 
country 
but those same legislators sat stonily silent when he repeated 
the us complaint that seoul needs to do more to reduce trade 
barriers 
in tokyo bush met with leaders of jordan egypt and israel in 
what the white house said was part of the search for peace in the 
region 
afterward bush said there were new opportunities in the 
middle east but there was no sign that the united states was ready 
to step in and try to capitalize on them 
the white house was sensitive about suggestions that it is going 
slowly and having trouble getting its act together 
the worst thing you could do the most foolish thing you could 
do is to try and enact foreign policy in a period of time measured 
in days or even a few weeks after having been inaugurated said 
white house chief of staff john sununu 
even if it were sound policy he said it probably would 
have been perceived as doing something rashly and quickly without 
consultation 
the other side of the coin is that bush risks losing the 
opportunity afforded a new administration for change and innovation 
in the first days of its life already it seems to be settling down 
to business as usual from the reagan administration and the 
honeymoon with congress seems to be evaporating 
</TEXT>
