a consortium of businesses and research 
institutions hopes a visit to albuquerque will be like life on 
another planet for some space engineers and scientists in the 1990s 
the national aeronautics and space administration is expected to 
decide by 1992 whether to recommend lunar colonization or a manned 
mission to mars in the early 21st century 
in preparation los alamos national laboratory the university of 
new mexico the air force the army corps of engineers and several 
new mexico businesses are proposing the nations first 
extraterrestrial environment simulator in albuquerque at an 
estimated cost of about 55 million 
this fits right in with lovelace medical center in 
albuquerque picking the mercury astronauts los alamos spokesman 
jeff schwartz said in a telephone interview monday new mexico has 
been at the frontier of the space age since there was a space age 
members of the consortium met here monday with nasa officials to 
discuss the project called the center for extraterrestrial 
engineering and construction or cetec talks were expected to 
continue all week 
steve howe a program coordinator in los alamos energy and 
technology initiatives office said its possible to have cetec 
operating in 1 to two years he estimated a sixyear cost of about 
55 million 
thats less than a million a year he said 
about 65 scientists engineers contractors and government 
officials attended mondays session howe said 
he said the basic configuration of cetec would be a couple of 
tanks doing teleoperated or robotic experiments vacuum tanks 
that would simulate the conditions on the moon where theres no 
atmosphere 
he said experiments would address several key questions 
how do you dig how do you drill how do you lay foundations 
can you make concrete out of the soil can you make structural glass 
out of the soil can you extract oxygen from the soil to manufacture 
fuel 
consortium members would put up about 2 million worth of 
equipment land and expertise he said noting that the air force 
already has the 60footlong 16footdiameter steel vacuum tubes 
needed for the project at kirtland air force base in albuquerque 
we are ready to contribute that if nasa comes in and says were 
ready to go howe said 
he said rock formations in minnesota and iceland closely match 
