drug abuse among high school seniors continued 
to decline last year and reached its lowest level since 1975 a 
national survey released today showed 
the national high school seniors survey found a significant drop 
in cocaine use for the second year in a row as well as a decrease in 
use of crack cocaine and continuation of the gradual decline in use 
of marijuana 
we can safely say that these decreases suggest that high school 
seniors are hearing the messages about cocaines dangers and are 
avoiding drug use in general said charles r schuster director 
of the national institute on drug abuse sponsor of the survey 
however drug abuse in our youth still remains a major public 
health problem he said noting that one of every eight high 
school seniors tries cocaine before graduation and one of every two 
seniors has used an illegal drug at least once 
the survey which has been conducted by the university of 
michigans institute for social research every year since 1975 
found that the proportion of high school seniors who reported having 
ever used an illegal drug dropped to 539 percent in 1988 that is 
the lowest level recorded since the survey began when the rate was 
552 percent 
while the use of marijuana has been declining since a peak of 
277 percent in the high school class of 1979 the level reported 
for last year 214 percent remains higher than the rate of 19 
percent reported in the first year of the survey 
the proportion of seniors who have used cocaine at least once 
dropped from 15 percent in 1987 to 12 percent in 1988 and the 
proportion who said they had used cocaine at least once in the last 
30 days dropped from 43 percent in 1987 to 34 percent in 1988 
the survey also showed that 40 percent of those who had tried 
cocaine also have used crack a cheap and highly addictive form of 
cocaine however the proportion of those who said they had used 
crack at least once dropped from 56 percent in 1987 to 48 percent 
last year 
some 16300 high school seniors from 135 schools nationwide were 
questioned for the survey 
