<TEXT>
the supreme court today reinstated a convicted 
florida murderers death sentence saying he should have been barred 
from mounting a successful constitutional attack in federal courts 
by a 54 vote the court ruled that aubrey adams jr forfeited 
the right to challenge his sentence in federal court on an issue he 
had failed to raise in state appellate courts 
adams was convicted of strangling 8yearold trisa gail thornley 
in ocala 11 years ago 
his conviction and death sentence were upheld three times by the 
florida supreme court before being overturned by a federal appeals 
court 
adams sought federal court review of his case in early 1986 
arguing for the first time that the trial judges instructions 
misled jurors about their role in determining what punishment adams 
should receive 
under florida law a jury recommends life or death for convicted 
murderers in capital cases the presiding judge is free to follow or 
disregard the recommendation 
the judge in adams case told jurors about that aspect of the 
states capitalsentencing law adding the final decision as to 
what punishment shall be imposed rests solely upon the judge of this 
court 
adams argued successfully before the 11th us circuit court of 
appeals that the judges instructions ran afoul of a 1985 supreme 
court decision in which the justices said a death sentence is 
invalid if a jury is misled about its role in determining whether 
the defendant actuall will die 
in the 1985 decision the justices reversed a mississippi 
murderers death sentence because a prosecutor told jurors their 
decision would be reviewed automatically by an appeals court 
writing for the court today justice byron r white said the 11th 
circuit court never should have reached the merits of adams appeal 
white said adams failure to raise the juryinstruction issue in 
his state court appeals precluded him from raising it in a socalled 
habeas corpus appeal in federal court 
the ground for challenging the trial judges instructions 
that they were objectionable under state law was a necessary 
element of the subsequently available claim arising from the 1985 
decision in the mississippi case white said 
his opinion was joined by chief justice william h rehnquist and 
justices sandra day oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy 
justices harry a blackmun william j brennan thurgood marshall 
and john paul stevens dissented 
the case is dugger vs adams 87121 
