<TEXT>
a movement is under way to preserve the 
home of a black writer whose violent death went unpunished because 
of precivil war legal discrimination 
william johnson a successful barber businessman and diarist is 
considered by historians the most prominent free black man in 
antebellum mississippi 
freed from slavery by his white owner in louisiana johnson built 
a threestory brick home in this blufflined mississippi river town 
in the early 1840s it remained in his family until purchased in 
1976 by a garden club 
what many people do not realize is that natchez had almost half 
of the states entire free black population before the war said 
mimi miller a historic preservation consultant what made johnson 
so important was that he kept a diary that represents the most 
complete and accurate account of a free black man during this period 
of our history 
miller who has worked with the natchez garden club to preserve 
the home said that through johnsons writings historians were 
able to learn that just as in the white society different levels 
of social class existed within the free black society this society 
was separate and distinct from blacks who were slaves 
the diary and other information indicates johnson was accepted 
and respected by the community and when he died in 1851 he 
received a very large obituary but the great and tragic thing is his 
death went unpunished because he was black miller said 
johnson apparently was shot by a man named baylor winn after a 
long dispute over land boundaries 
only blacks witnessed the shooting and under mississippi law at 
the time a black man could not testify against a white man miller 
said winn represented himself as white but prosecutors in hopes of 
allowing the testimony of black witnesses argued he had some black 
ancestry 
natchez was so outraged they had to move his trial to another 
town so winn could get an impartial jury she said the johnson 
family hired an attorney will t martin who later became one of 
mississippis highest ranking confederate generals 
despite martins efforts winn went free 
johnsons house proved to be a historical treasure trove 
containing much more than the 16year diary which was published by 
the louisiana state university press in 1951 
in the attic were nearly 1400 legal and financial documents 
personal and business correspondence volumes of account books and 
old newspapers and sheet music dating from 1793 said margaret moss 
of the natchez garden club 
miller said preservationists hope to use the homes ground floor 
for an exhibit on natchezs black history and restore the living 
quarters upstairs with period furnishings 
in 1987 the legislature authorized the states archives and 
history department to buy restore and administer the home once 
sufficient funds are secured said director elbert hilliard the 
effort will require a 15 million endowment hilliard said 
an advisory committee has been formed to study ways to raise 
money from private sources meanwhile the national trust for 
historic preservation and the jack daniel foundation for preserving 
american landmarks and traditions is working on raising 4000 to 
make immediate repairs 
