<TEXT>
tight limits on the nuclear regulatory 
commission budget during the reagan administration seriously hurt 
the agencys search for ways to improve nuclear plant safety the 
commission chairman told congress on tuesday 
lando w zech jr told a house energy and commerce subcommittee 
that since 1984 the agencys budget had declined even as attention 
to safety needs had increased 
the reductions have had a significant impact on our safety 
research program over the years zech said we believe this 
trend must be reversed 
the nrcs current budget is 426 million compared with 466 
million in 1984 
in presenting the commissions request for an 11 percent overall 
budget increase to 475 million for the year beginning oct 1 zech 
said half the extra money was urgently needed to strengthen 
safety programs 
zech told the panel the safety record of the nations 108 fully 
operating nuclear power plants had improved in recent years but 
stressed that more work was needed by regulators as well as plant 
owners to make nuclear power more reliable 
we have not yet achieved excellence across the board in 
nuclear plant operations he said although plant owners are taking 
safety requirements more seriously 
zech said the nrc with a bigger budget for safety programs 
would increase the number of agency staffers assigned as resident 
inspectors at nuclear plants the commission currently has at least 
one such inspector at each plant 
we believed that the nrc resident inspection program has played 
a significant role in improving industry safety performance and that 
the expansion of the program is necessary to achieve further 
improvements zech said 
the commission chairman also said an agency decision was due as 
early as next week on a proposed rule change aimed at speeding up 
licensing for nuclear plants 
the change would allow utilities to get federal approval for a 
construction permit and an operating license before starting the 
project under current rules the nrc does not consider the 
operating license application until after the construction has 
begun as a result utilities in some cases have completed plants 
but been unable to win approval to operate them 
zech called the proposed change an historic ruling although 
he added that he was still reviewing the proposal and had not 
decided whether to vote for it several members of the committee 
told zech they strongly favored the change 
rep bob clement dtenn said the commission should move 
quickly to adopt the streamlined licensing system in order to 
encourage expansion of nuclear power 
without standardization and licensing reform it is very 
unlikely that there will be additional orders of commercial nuclear 
plants clement said no orders have been placed for nuclear 
plants since 1979 the year of the three mile island reactor 
accident in pennsylvania that raised new safety concerns 
zech also told the panel the nrc was preparing to adopt shortly a 
regulation requiring random drug and alcohol testing of employees at 
all nuclear plants 
</TEXT>
