<TEXT>
more than a dozen eminent chinese intellectuals on 
tuesday criticized a proposed dam on the yangtze river as an 
illconsidered wasteful project that would serve only as a memorial 
to its builders 
in a move extremely rare in this authoritarian society the 
informal alliance of of writers engineers and former government 
officials held a news conference to issue a book criticizing the 
hydroelectric project 
there is only one yangtze river and it belows to the entire 
nation and all mankind said dai qing a newspaper editor who 
compiled the book of essays mankind should not abuse it 
we have discussed this back and forth for more than 30 years 
and still cannot resolve the problems said 96yearold sun yueqi 
who heads the economic committee of the chinese peoples political 
consultative committee a prestigious but powerless body of 
intellectuals 
when it comes to producing electricity the dam is no good and 
it will destroy river shipping he said 
the government is in the final stages of studying the proposed 
three gorges hyroelectric project which calls for a 610foothigh 
dam in central china where the mighty yangtze passes through 
towering cliffs eulogized by chinese poets for centuries 
the project would generate up to 17000 megawatts of electricity 
cost estimates range from the official one of about 10 billion to 
some critics estimate of 30 billion 
the idea of harnessing energy from the rivers turbulent passage 
through the three gorges in hubei province first was suggested in 
the 1920s it has been considered repeatedly over the years but 
never acted upon because of the huge expense engineering difficulty 
and what critics say would be serious damage to the environment and 
river shipping 
nearly 1 million people would have to be moved to make way for a 
vast new reservoir the area also has been hit by earthquakes in the 
past and some critics say a quake could crack the dam and cause a 
massive disaster 
leading writer zhang jie told the news conference that backers of 
the project have not evaluated it scientifically but look on it as a 
sort of personal monument we dont want to put up a memorial 
plaque that will win much fame but little benefit she said 
premier li peng formerly minister of power is believed to be 
one of its main supporters proponents say the project would help 
solve chinas energy shortage control flooding and make the upper 
reaches of the river accessible to larger ships 
a canadian consortium of government and corporate experts 
concluded after a twoyear study that the project is feasible and 
rejected many of the objections of the critics however the critics 
noted that several companies in the consortium are potential bidders 
for dam contracts 
tuesdays news conference was the first time a group of 
intellectuals dared to band together and express their opposition 
publicly 
ms dai said the debate had to brought out into the open 
ordinary people know that many large projects have a direct 
impact on them individually she said if the project goes well 
it is called government funded but in reality everyone who pays 
taxes pays for it out of his own pocket ordinary people cannot 
afford not to hear all the viewpoints 
li rui who was vice minister of hydroelectric power in the 1950s 
and vice minister of water conservancy in the early 1980s said 
instead of building one massive dam smaller dams should be built on 
tributaries of the yangtze 
wu jing a senior government engineer who came to listen agreed 
wu said that across town several hundred government experts were 
holding one of a series of meetings to discuss the latest official 
feasibility study 
were having competing meetings he chuckled 
</TEXT>
