<TEXT>
colorados fourmonth oxygenated fuels program to 
cut carbon monoxide pollution ended tuesday without having created 
the stir that clouded the mandatory programs debut last year 
there just wasnt the attention on it this year since everybody 
had gone through it once said ted hollman senior air pollution 
control specialist for the state health department 
once people found out all the doomsday predictions didnt come 
true they stopped thinking about it he said 
mechanics in the denver area reported few problems as a result of 
the oxygenated fuels although older cars had more trouble than 
newer ones 
as for suppliers john augustine of conoco said the program was 
much smoother this year because we had a lot of lead time we 
had the whole year to know its coming and get the tanks and 
everything ready 
conoco even plans to continue offering an ethanolblended 
gasoline after the program ends and see how the sales go 
augustine said 
state rep tom ratterree a critic of the program mainly because 
it is mandatory said he still believes the fuels are creating 
problems in peoples cars and motorists simply arent aware of the 
cause 
the car may not run but they dont know why ratterree said 
if i were to generate an awareness level out there then people 
would come out of the woodwork again 
the program was in effect along colorados front range from fort 
collins and greeley in the north to colorado springs in the south 
including the denver area 
the oxygenated fuels are actually blends of ordinary gasoline and 
either grain alcohol ethanol or the etherbased mtbe nearly 2 
million cars and trucks ran on the fuels every day hollman said 
at denvers milehigh altitude ordinary fuel burns incompletely 
in engines and the unexpended fuel emitted into the air adds to 
pollution especially during winter months when temperature 
inversions trap the smog highoxygen fuels burn more cleanly 
last year the oxygenated fuels program ran just two months and 
cut carbon monoxide emissions an average 95 percent officials said 
this year the goal was 12 percent the amount of oxygen required 
in the fuels was increased from 15 percent to 2 percent resulting 
in the use of more ethanol hollman said 
preliminary results of the oxygenated fuels program and the 
threemonth better air campaign which ended in january and included 
voluntary nodrive days and voluntary and mandatory woodburning 
bans were expected later this week 
the combined programs last year dropped denver from first to 
seventh place on the environmental protection agencys list of worst 
cities for carbon monoxide pollution 
the rocky mountain oil and gas association a trade association 
for the industry opposes the programs mandatory provisions and 
disputes its environmental benefits 
as far as consumer satisfaction consumers are relatively 
satisfied because there has been a choice of oxygenated fuels 
said special projects director pam oldham 
</TEXT>
