<TEXT>
the us trade deficit worsened in the final 
three months of the year climbing to 32 billion as both us 
exports and imports hit record levels the government reported 
tuesday 
the commerce department said the deficit from october through 
december swelled by 10 percent from a third quarter deficit of 
2917 billion 
the trade deficit had shown steady improvement through the first 
three quarters of 1988 helping to push the deficit for the entire 
year down to 1265 billion 217 percent below the alltime high of 
16028 billion set in 1987 
while economists were pleased with the big improvement for the 
year they expressed fears that the improvement has now stalled and 
will hold back overall economic growth in 1989 
the trade deficit has stopped improving said david wyss an 
economist with data resources inc of lexington mass we made 
some big gains in exports in 1987 and 1988 but they havent been 
enough to balance our big appetite for imports 
tuesdays trade figures confirmed an improvement already noted in 
the commerce departments monthly merchandise trade reports those 
figures showed the deficit declining to 13734 billion in 1988 
down from 1703 billion in 1987 
the new report which measures trade on a balanceofpayments 
basis has smaller figures because it subtracts shipping costs and 
military sales from the monthly numbers 
another measure of trade contained in the report on the gross 
national product released tuesday also showed a worsening in the 
deficit for the fourth quarter of 1988 unlike the other trade 
figures the gnp report removes the effects of inflation from the 
import and export numbers 
the report on merchandise trade on a balanceofpayments basis 
showed that exports rose 2 billion to a record level of 836 
billion in the fourth quarter while imports climbed 48 billion to 
a record 1157 billion 
the trade deficit with japan also set a record rising by 32 
billion to 155 billion in the fourth quarter 
the largest increase in imports came in autos up 18 billion 
reflecting higher shipments from south korea japan and mexico 
imports of consumer goods including apparel and household goods 
rose by 16 billion 
on the export side shipments of manufactured goods rose 4 
percent while farm shipments fell by 6 percent 
for the year the decline in the deficit to 1265 billion 
reflected a 28 percent surge in export sales and a 9 percent rise in 
imports 
but wyss said he expected little further improvement in 1989 
saying the trade performance will not move off current high levels 
until the dollar weakens further making imports even more expensive 
and us goods more competitive on overseas markets 
nonfarm exports rose 28 percent to 616 billion in 1988 with 
the largest increases in sales of us capital equipment and 
industrial supplies 
agricultural exports shot up 30 percent to 383 billion their 
highest level since 1984 
the largest increases were in sales of corn which were up 19 
billion reflecting higher sales to the soviet union japan and 
taiwan and in wheat which also climbed by 19 billion reflecting 
higher shipments to china and the soviet union 
the farm sales increase reflected in part higher prices caused by 
the severe drought the average price of corn was up 38 percent for 
the year while the price of soybeans rose by 33 percent wheat 
prices were up 20 percent and cotton prices rose 20 percent 
