<TEXT>
a public television station that pioneered closed 
captions for the hearing impaired has developed a new service that 
makes television vivid for the blind 
by tuning a special channel on a stereo television or home video 
recorder the service allows blind people to hear a narrator 
describe the action in a program between pauses in dialogue 
bostons public station wgbh tested the service last year and 
is now seeking funding to make it available to the nations 
estimated 12 million visually impaired people in january 1990 
i never realized when i watched television from a listening 
perspective that i was missing so much kim charlson recalled 
tuesday blind since the age of 11 the 31yearold watertown 
resident was among thousands of visually impaired people across the 
country who tuned in last year to the services trial run 
television is a major means of communiciation in society 
mrs charlson said theres so much on television you tend to 
feel left out when you cant access it i really commend them that 
theyre trying to do it and do it right 
the new development called descriptive video services allows 
people with visual impairment or even sighted people stepping away 
from their television set to follow the action all they need is a 
stereo television set or vcr that can be tuned to the separate audio 
program channel or sap during a musical interlude or breaks in 
dialogue a narrator is heard above the background music 
wgbh enlisted nine other public tv stations to test the service 
from january to july 1988 on the pbs american playhouse drama 
series stations participated in washington dc metropolitan new 
york city and rochester in new york cleveland and bowling green 
ohio milwaukee dallas pensacola fla and lewiston maine 
a viewer tuned to the play lemon sky for example could hear 
as the credits rolled a mountain silhouette in the distance palm 
trees closer a boys bike between a high brown wooden fence in 
the foreground a white mid50s convertible gleaming in the sun its 
top down 
then later after a character spoke his lines he strolls away 
from the car toward the house pausing in the doorway 
i see it as something that can become widely popular and should 
be said john de witt who evaluates hightech aides for the blind 
at the american federation for the blind in new york 
its not a question only of people who are totally blind de 
witt said in a telephone interview there are millions of people 
who have very poor vision and cannot see small details on the 
screen people who are losing their vision at any time of life 
credit for the idea is given to margaret pfanstiehl founder of 
metropolitan washington ear a radio reading service based in silver 
spring md ms pfanstiehl found a way for theaters to offer 
narration for blind people with audio headsets 
it became accessible for television through stereo tv and vcrs 
after establishment of the separate audio program channel about five 
years ago about 10 percent of american homes can tap the audio 
channel now but laurie everett director of descriptive video 
services predicted they will be commonplace before the turn of the 
century 
in a couple of years you wont be able to buy a television that 
isnt stereo she said 
wgbh is trying to raise funds to launch the service nationally 
five hours a week ms everett said needing 300000 to start up 
and another 1 million annually 
it was 15 years ago that wgbh pioneered closed captioning for the 
deaf with a decoding device viewers can see subtitles across the 
screen captioning is now available on 65 percent of all prime time 
tv its used widely by publicly funded tv as well as on commercial 
cable and videotaped films 
</TEXT>
