president bush on tuesday announced his choices 
for several subcabinetlevel state department posts including the 
selection of bernard aronson to succeed elliott abrams as assistant 
secretary of state for interamerican affairs 
aronson 41 is a democrat who served as a white house 
speechwriter for president jimmy carter and later was policy 
director for the democratic national committee more recently 
aronson headed the policy project a consulting firm in washington 
among other announced state department nominations all requiring 
senate confirmation were 
douglas mulholland to be assistant secretary of state for 
intelligence and research succeeding morton abramowitz 
mulholland was an analyst for domestic policy and research for 
the bush presidential campaign committee he held several positions 
at the cia between 195679 
richard armitage to be assistant secretary of state for east 
asian and pacific affairs succeeding gaston sigur 
since 1983 armitage has been assistant secretary of defense for 
international security affairs he previously served as an 
administrative assistant to sen bob dole rkan in 197879 
john h kelly to be an assistant secretary of state for near 
east and south asian affairs succeeding richard murphy 
kelly has been the principal deputy director of the policy 
planning staff at the state department since last year before that 
he was the us ambassador to lebanon from 1986 to 1988 
herman jay cohen to be assistant secretary of state for african 
affairs succeeding chester a crocker 
from 1987 until the present time cohen had been the senior 
director for african affairs on the national security council staff 
at the white house he held several positions previously at the 
state department 
john bolton to be an assistant secretary of state for 
international organization affairs succeeding richard williamson 
bolton has been assistant attorney general in charge of the civil 
division of the justice department since last year before that he 
was assistant attorney general in the office of legislative affairs 
and had been a partner in the washington law firm of covington amp 
burling 
