<TEXT>
a district of columbia judge rejected 
dissenting theologian charles currans suit against catholic 
university of america on tuesday ruling the school was within its 
rights in barring him from teaching theology there 
judge frederick weisberg said that in a struggle between academic 
freedom and obedience to pope john paul ii the university may 
choose for itself on which side of that conflict it wants to come 
down 
curran a priest strongly criticized by vatican officials for his 
positions on abortion homosexuality and other matters of sexual 
ethics had argued in court that the school breached his contract by 
removing him from the moral theology courses he had taught for years 
he sought full reinstatement in his lawsuit in superior court 
maintaining the university violated his contract as a tenured 
professor 
in a written decision the judge said it is apparent that this 
dispute is merely a piece of the larger struggle that has been 
raging in catholic higher education for many years that struggle 
seeks to establish the proper role of academic freedom within an 
american catholic university 
curran said he would not appeal 
i have fought for academic freedom at catholic university for 
more than 20 years he said in a statement distributed by his 
lawyers i have lost as far as i am concerned this was the last 
battle 
later in a telephone interview he said i think that catholic 
university was on trial more than i was i think the judge was 
wrong 
university officials said they felt vindicated 
it doesnt surprise me to tell you the truth said the rev 
william byron president of the school this is really what i 
expected because we never breached his contract 
curran who had taught at catholic university since 1965 was 
suspended in early 1987 and was formally told last year that he 
could not return as a theology teacher since his departure he has 
taught as a visiting professor at cornell university and then at the 
university of southern california 
catholic universitys action against him followed a vatican 
declaration that he was no longer suitable or eligible to teach 
catholic theology because of his dissenting views 
curran testified during his sevenday trial in december that 
under principles of academic freedom prevailing at american 
universities a tenured faculty member may be removed from his post 
only if his colleagues believe he is incompetent 
university officials testified that their action was proper under 
the schools special relationship with the vatican 
the catholic church requires theology professors at the school to 
have special authorization called a canonical mission cardinal 
james a hickey chancellor of the school testified the schools 
board of trustees withdrew currans canonical mission last april 
curran contended the canonical mission requirement had fallen 
into disuse in the 1960s when he joined the schools faculty he 
argued that he had never had a canonical mission so it could not be 
taken away curran also said a 1981 church rule making canonical 
missions mandatory did not apply to him because it wasnt in effect 
when he joined the faculty 
hickey said that although the requirement was not spelled out in 
church documents in the 1960s it was implicit 
curran said during the trial he wanted to prove that in the 
last analysis academic freedom itself is for the good of the 
church 
but weisberg said in his ruling what is good for catholic 
university or for the roman catholic church is not a question 
presented and not one the court has either the right or the 
competence to decide the question presented is whether his contract 
gives him the right to teach catholic theology at catholic 
university in the face of a definitive judgment from the holy see 
that he is ineligible to do so 
the court holds today that it does not 
</TEXT>
