<TEXT>
the huge pressure vessel from the 
worlds first dismantled commercial nuclear reactor began its 
8100mile journey tuesday to washington state for burial 
the 1000ton vessel and neutronshield tank from shippingport 
the nations first commercial nuclear plant left the area about 
350 pm and was expected to arrive in the us energy departments 
dump at hanford wash in about 60 days department spokesman tom 
bauman said 
everything went smoothly and there were no problems bauman 
said 
the vessel and tank were packed in concrete and lifted onto the 
200foot seagoing barge paul bunyan in the ohio river last month 
the trip was delayed until tuesday because of poor weather 
the speed of the barges progress along the route down the ohio 
and mississippi rivers and through the gulf of mexico to the panama 
canal and the pacific ocean also will depend on the weather bauman 
said 
the reactor vessel was hoisted from its underground site at 
shippingport about 30 miles from pittsburgh on dec 14 
the shippingport plant was dedicated by president eisenhower in 
1957 and retired in 1982 after generating 65 billion kilowatthours 
of electricity 
it is the worlds only commercial reactor to be dismantled 
several nuclear plants have been mothballed or entombed 
the government hopes to show that reactors that have outlived 
their usefulness can be dismantled safely and affordably 
federal officials intend to remove all radioactive material so 
the shippingport site can be returned to unrestricted use no 
decision has been made as to how to use the land 
the decommissioning which has lasted five years is expected to 
be completed by 1990 at a cost of about 98 million 
</TEXT>
