<TEXT>
the directors of the national transplant 
network on tuesday adopted a policy discouraging the use of babies 
who were born without most of their brains but are not yet brain 
dead as organ donors 
however the board of the united network for organ sharing said 
it would be unwise to totally prohibit using anencephalic babies as 
organ donors 
experts and ethicists have been divided for some time over 
whether to transplant the hearts livers and kidneys of anencephalic 
infants into other dying babies for whom there is an extreme 
shortage of organs 
anencephalic infants are born with only part of a brain stem 
which controls respiration because they do have slight brain stem 
activity they are not legally brain dead which is required before 
organs can be removed 
by the time such infants are brain dead their organs often are 
not fit for transplantation because of infection 
half of the 1000 to 2000 anencephalic babies born each year in 
the united states are stillborn the other half generally die within 
one week 
only one anencephalic child has ever had its organs removed for 
transplantation in the united states that case on oct 16 1987 
involved a canadian donor and recipient and was performed at loma 
linda university medical center in california 
the heart recipient a boy who was born the day of the operation 
is at home and doing well said hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell 
loma linda has had a moratorium since august on cases involving 
infants suffering from the incurable birth defect 
anencephalic infants reportedly have been used with family 
consent as organ donors in canada europe and japan 
what the recommendation says is that people for the time 
being approach the use of infants with anencephaly with extreme 
caution that it would not be wise to use any such baby as an organ 
donor until a consensus has been reached about how to pronounce 
death in a newborn art caplan director of the center for 
biomedical ethics at the university of minnesota said in a 
telephone interview from minneapolis 
caplan was part of an ethics committee that recently presented 
the recommendation to the networks 32member board of directors 
the virginiabased network administers the national organ 
procurement and transplantation network 
the board adopted the position during a regular meeting in new 
orleans members include doctors organ procurement officials 
ethicists theologians lawyers and healthcare finance 
administrators 
the board concluded that a moratorium would not be wise because 
it would preclude organ donations by anencephalic infants who are 
brain dead and whose parents strongly desire to donate their childs 
organs said dr jeremiah g turcotte chairman of the ethics 
committee 
the board said further study is needed and could prompt a 
reevaluation of its position 
brian broznick director of the pittsburgh transplant foundation 
said there likely would be enough organs for the 400 to 500 children 
awaiting liver transplants in the united states if anencephalic 
infants were used as donors 
we could probably take care of all those kids and we cant do 
anything about it broznick said its a real sad situation 
</TEXT>
