intended to ease strains between the vatican and 
us catholicism an extraordinary summit meeting convenes next week 
between american archbishops and pope john paul ii 
he calls the concentrated four days of talks a fraternal 
encounter archbishops say they expect a friendly mutually 
cooperative mood 
this isnt shaping up as a confrontation but rather as a 
helpful exchange of views among church leaders looking for ways to 
work together effectively says cardinal joseph bernardin of 
chicago 
several of the earlier tensions have faded but others remain 
such as the handling of dissent from church regulations and the 
status of the bishops national organization itself 
that in a way is perhaps most important says the rev 
thomas j reeske of washington d c whose research has made him a 
leading authority on attitudes of us bishops 
he added in an interview 
the issue is whether episcopal conferences have the right and 
authority to teach and make decisions that have an impact on the 
life of the church in the united states or whether all the 
decisions are to be made in rome 
the trend has been toward centralizing decisions in rome 
differences with the vatican both on approaches to dissent and 
the rights of the bishops national conference showed up only at 
their meeting last november 
the vatican intervened to get them to postpone acting on their 
document doctrinal responsibilities on dealing with dissent 
also the bishops disapproved a vatican draft minimizing the role 
of bishops conferences 
it was returned as unsuitable even as a basis for discussion 
the bishops and the vatican also temporarily differed over makeup 
of the summit meeting itself they in 15 regional sessions last 
fall had elected representatives to attend but the vatican said 
no it wanted only archbishops 
that was another slight of the bishops conferences reese 
said adding their elected representatives would have had some 
kind of mandate but thats not directly the case with the 
archbishops 
twentyone of the 35 us participants in the march 911 vatican 
meeting were appointed by the present pope the agenda says theyll 
have more than 12 hours of open discussion with him and heads of his 
cabinet the curia 
the theme in generalizing vatican terminology is 
evangelization in the context of the culture and society of the 
united states of america with particular emphasis on the role of the 
bishop as teacher of the faith 
the opaque language refers to the impact of christian values on 
society and culture a special concern of the pope examining that 
big picture ought to be a positive thing reese said the 
danger is the talk will just be in the abstract 
reese of woodstock theological center at washingtons georgetown 
university has individually interviewed the countrys archbishops 
for his forthcoming book archbishop inside the power structure 
of the american catholic church to be published in may by harper 
amp row 
he predicted conflict will be minimal at the vatican meeting 
on various matters such as the popes insistence on individual 
confession before first communion and his criticism of a previously 
extensive practice of giving general absolution without confession 
