<TEXT>
five former du pont co employees 
threatened to sell secret documents on synthetic fibers to a 
competitor or begin production themselves if the chemical giant 
didnt pay them 10 million authorities said 
four of the five were arrested on extortion charges monday in 
switzerland in a hotel parking lot after they failed to meet with du 
pont officials and an undercover fbi agent where an exchange was to 
take place said fbi agent joseph v corless 
du pont had planned to turn over a bogus 10 million check for 
the documents which deal with the production of lycra the 
companys trade name for spandex fiber used in clothing such as 
swimming suits leotards and pantyhose 
the suspects also were to sign a contract agreeing not to produce 
spandex fiber for five years corless said 
the five had worked at the du pont plant in mercedes argentina 
one of several plants that make spandex du pont was contacted about 
the documents in december four of the five had quit since 
september authorities said 
those arrested were bruno skerianz age unknown raul a 
giordano 36 operations supervisor for lycra production antonio r 
inigo 39 maintenance supervisor for lycra production and maria i 
lorenzo de bianchini 39 secretary of the lycra information office 
authorities said 
corless said ms de bianchini had the most access to the 
documents 
skerianz who worked at the plant about 20 years ago was 
believed to be the ringleader and recruited the others while they 
were working for du pont the others had been du pont employees for 
13 or 14 years 
a warrant was issued for jose m petrosino 44 specialist 
engineer for lycra processing who remained at large 
william carpenter an assistant us attorney said the five have 
been charged with one count each of attempted extortion and if 
convicted face up to 20 years in prison and a 250000 fine 
there are being held by swiss authorities and the united states 
will seek extradition corless said 
corless said the documents were recovered but he admitted there 
were no guarantees that copies had not been made 
considering du pont was willing to pay we hope there are no 
more copies he said we still have a lot of investigating to 
do 
john r malloy du pont spokesman at its wilmington headquarters 
said the information was very valuable and probably would have 
enabled them to set up a competing plant 
after the suspects contacted du pont several meetings were held 
inside and outside the united states and telephone calls were made 
to discuss the documents corless said skerianz met with du pont 
officials in wilmington and offered to sell the company certain 
spandex technology the fbi said 
corless said that skerianz refused to bring the documents to the 
united states but du pont officials examined the approximately 
1000 documents at a meeting in milan italy in january 
