<TEXT>
the federal government should extend the current 
limits on imported steel to avoid more dumping of the metal on us 
markets a leading steel industry executive says 
the current voluntary restraint agreement is to expire at the end 
of september and a fiveyear extension has been recommended to the 
bush administration 
without the renewal president thomas graham of usx corps uss 
division said monday overseas steel producers will invade the us 
market 
theres no doubt that foreign producers will revert to 
largescale dumping of heavily subsidized steel without a 
restraints renewal he said we certainly cant tolerate a return 
to past practices 
in the third quarter of 1984 shortly before the restraints 
began imported steel made up just more than 30 percent of the us 
market 
grahams comments came during the opening day of the weeklong 
annual congress of the society of automotive engineers 
he said the voluntary restraints renewal is essential if the us 
steel industry is to continue its twoyear financial recovery 
we cant afford to become giddy he said two years of 
profitability doesnt offset five years of losses 
graham said the us steel industry earned more than 2 billion 
in 1988 and about 900 million the year before but between 1982 and 
1986 the industry lost 12 billion an average of 24 billion 
annually 
the voluntary restraint agreement which began in 1984 limits 
the amount of imported finished steel to 185 percent of the us 
market among other things the american institute for imported 
steel said steel made overseas and shipped to the united states 
accounts for about 177 percent of the market below the current 
limit 
the imported steel association which supports an elimination of 
the restraints or a twoyear extension instead of five years has 
claimed that the limits reduce supply thereby increasing prices for 
us steel something the domestic steelmakers like 
but graham dismissed that contention 
its not an issue of protectionism he said its an issue 
of legal trading practices 
graham also said uss is prepared to file legal papers if the bush 
administration rejects a voluntary restraints extension 
we need enabling legislation from congress before the bush 
administration has the ability to act he said we see ourselves 
as prudent businessmen 
he declined to say when any legal moves may be taken adding that 
an earlier agreement barred the industry from filing trade 
litigation while a voluntary restraint was in effect 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

