general motors corp said tuesday it will spend 
975 million to buy blocks of stock from the howard hughes medical 
institute to settle a dispute stemming from the automakers 1985 
purchase of hughes aircraft co 
the institute a philanthropic organization founded by the late 
billionaire recluse had complained to gm officials that it wasnt 
satisifed with the performance of gms class h common stock 
gm said it would pay 675 million in cash and 300 million in 
notes to buy 35 million shares of the stock which was created to 
help finance the 52 billion purchase of hughes aircraft in june 
1985 
the medical institute now owns 995 million or about 78 percent 
of the outstanding shares of gm class h stock 
the agreement resolves a dispute that went to arbitration late 
last year gm treasurer leon krain refused to disclose the reasons 
for the arbitration which kicked in under terms of the 1985 hughes 
deal 
gm reportedly was seeking a rebate on what it paid for hughes 
because the company lost some defense department contracts it had 
before the purchase was made 
the institute in december complained about light trading of the 
class h stock which made up the bulk of its assets and that the 
price of the shares appeared mainly tied to a 30ashare price 
guarantee 
when hughes aircraft became gm hughes electronics corp the 
automaker promised to pay the institute the difference between 30 a 
share and the average price for class h stock during the last 
quarter of 1989 that provision was canceled by the agreement 
the new agreement calls for a series of stock purchase and sell 
options for gm and the institute from 1991 to 1995 if all are 
exercised the medical institute would hold about 95 million 
shares or 75 percent of the outstanding class h stock 
the agreement requires that the institute hold its class h stock 
until each option deadline passes 
gm chairman roger b smith said the company which has reported 
that it has 68 billion in cash on hand could afford the stock 
purchase plans called for in the agreement he said the agreement 
will provide the institute with cash liquidity it had sought 
bob potter spokesman for the bethesda mdbased medical 
institute said the 675 million in cash go into an investment fund 
the remaining 300 million is to be split between two notes 
money generated from the investment fund will go to a variety of 
projects including medical research potter said in a statement 
institute chairman george thorn said the money will allow better 
planning of research and other capital expenditure programs 
