<TEXT>
congress should tax stock trading to discourage 
socially wasteful financial speculation a harvard university 
economist argued in a tuesday speech but a wall street executive 
said such a policy could increase the chance of sharp price declines 
economist lawrence h summers a top economic adviser to the 
democratic presidential campaign of michael dukakis said 
unproductive shortterm trading had helped the financial industry 
grow out of proportion to economic sectors that produce food cars 
and other useful products 
the tax proposal made during a conference on financial market 
technology reflects sentiment against speculation that has been 
gathering strength in washington as well as academic and corporate 
circles he said 
summers said for example that treasury secretary nicholas 
brady a former wall street executive has indicated he was 
committed to reduce incentives that make companies focus on 
quarterly profits to appease shortterm investors and concurrently 
create greater opportunities for speculation 
but louis i margolis a managing director of salomon brothers 
inc said summers proposed tax on stock trades would make sharp 
price declines likelier by reducing the number of investors who 
would be willing to buy a falling stock 
we are coming along to a liquidity crisis in the stock 
market margolis said 
weve seen the traditional swings between optimism and 
pessimism compressed into very short periods of time he said 
the debate came on the second and main day of a forum sponsored 
by the annenberg washington program and northwestern universitys 
kellogg graduate school of management 
in addition to political issues the conference dealt with how to 
manage computers and highspeed communications so that they make the 
markets more efficient without making them vulnerable to cataclysms 
like the october 1987 stock market crash 
the threat of japanese competition accounts for the urgency of 
american efforts to improve the speed and efficiency of the markets 
william brodsky the president of the chicago mercantile exchange 
said in an afternoon session 
japan is probably the most important reason the chicago merc 
has developed a 24hour global electronic trading system in 
cooperation with reuters holdings plc brodsky said 
japan is a competitive threat for us in futures just as they 
are in semiconductors automobiles and other things he said 
the merc intends to preserve its open outcry trading system 
during regular hours even after adopting an electronic system for 
off hours brodsky said in a session following the faceoff between 
summers and his critics 
summers said a tax of 05 percent on stock trades would raise 
about 10 billion a year and would be small enough to discourage 
only the major market players who he said contribute to sharp swings 
in stock prices 
he said bond trading also be could taxed perhaps at a lower 
rate other countries including britain and japan tax transactions 
so a tax would be unlikely to drive business offshore he said 
salomons margolis said a better solution than taxation for 
curbing speculation would be a return to fixed commissions for 
brokers 
he said big wall street houses that traditionally helped 
stabilize markets by absorbing dumped stock are already shrinking 
their brokerage businesses because commissions are too small to be 
worthwhile 
acknowledging that investors would not likely tolerate going back 
to fixed commissions margolis said an alternative would be to free 
brokerage firms from certain current regulatory constraints 
wall street firms should be freed to trade oddsized bundles of 
stocks and to make free use of the chicago stock options market to 
hedge their portfolios margolis said 
princeton university economist sanford grossman also criticized 
the proposed trading tax grossman said it was unfair to single out 
the securities industry for a tax and said there was no evidence 
that the financial markets were excessively volatile 
</TEXT>
