<TEXT>
lawyers for gaf corp asked a federal judge 
tuesday to dismiss the securities fraud case against the company 
saying federal prosecutors had not proven stock manipulation charges 
the governments case ended with the fact that one of its two 
principal witnesses testified that he didnt think he was 
manipulating stock in union carbide and he still doesnt think so 
defense lawyer max gitter said 
james t melton chief trader at the west coast brokerage firm 
jefferies amp co testified that while he sought to assure that union 
carbide stock closed at a specific price he had not attempted to 
deceive investors 
defense lawyers said stock manipulation charges were unfounded 
because the government had offered no proof gaf had intended to 
induce investors to buy the stock 
melton and broker boyd l jefferies were the governments key 
witnesses in the gaf case the first to be heard by a jury developed 
on information supplied by jailed speculator ivan boesky 
melton testifying under an immunity agreement reached with 
prosecutors backed up jefferies earlier testimony that he sought 
to inflate the stock price of union carbide corp to 22 a share in 
october 1986 
gaf and its vice chairman james t sherwin are charged with 
illegally trying through the stock purchases to raise the carbide 
stock price gaf held 10 million union carbide shares after an 
unsuccessful takeover attempt in november gaf sold 5 million 
shares for 23 each 
gitter said that while gaf naturally wanted to sell its union 
carbide holdings at the highest possible price neither gaf nor 
jefferies amp co did anything illegal in trying to boost the price of 
the shares 
the governments theory of market manipulation is not only 
novel its unsound gitter said there was no distortion of the 
market 
the defense also sought to have us district judge mary johnson 
lowe strike portions of jefferies testimony about melton on the 
grounds that it was hearsay and said the deletions would be so 
great as to require a mistrial 
prosecutors contentested the challenges and said the trial should 
continue lowe said she would consider the defense motion to dismiss 
the case and rule later 
assistant us attorney carl h loewenson jr argued that gaf and 
sherwin directed jefferies to make large purchases of union carbide 
near the close of trading on the new york and pacific stock 
exchanges on oct 29 and oct 30 1986 to push the closing price to 
22 or higher 
he said they entered the market not to make investments but to 
manipulate the price and induce investors to purchase union carbide 
what mr sherwin was interested in was boosting the price at a 
time his company held 10 million shares loewenson said 
the judge however indicated she was not convinced by the 
governments argument and said it would be difficult to determine 
gafs and sherwins motives 
how does one differentiate between the raising of stock prices 
in a legitimate trade in the market from an illegal trade lowe 
asked you cannot xray the mind of a person to determine what he 
is thinking at a particular time 
gaf was named in a 10count indictment handed up last july 
charging the wayne nj chemicals manufacturer with stock 
manipulation securities fraud wire fraud and conspiracy 
an earlier hearing ended in a mistrial in january when lowe found 
that a prosecutor had improperly but unintentionally withheld 
evidence 
