<TEXT>
a nuclear industry group tuesday praised 
management improvements by philadelphia electric co at its peach 
bottom nuclear plant which a year ago the group called a national 
embarrassment 
the institute of nuclear power operations said the utility has 
adequately addressed the industry groups three recommendations of a 
year ago 
it is evident to inpo and to other close observers that the 
company has made and is continuing to make considerable progress in 
achieving the necessary cultural change said zack t pate 
president of inpo in a letter to the utilitys chairman 
the federal nuclear regulatory commission ordered peach bottom 
closed in march 1987 when control room operators were found sleeping 
on the job the nrc said last month that the utility had made good 
on an ambitious plan designed to get the idled plant restarted as 
soon as april 
the letter from atlantabased inpo released tuesday by 
philadelphia electric was a sharp turnabout from the highly 
critical report of a year ago that described the utilitys 
performance as an embarrassment to the industry and the nation 
at the delta pa plant 
the group recommended a detailed analysis of the utilitys 
internal investigation of the plant that the utility avoid actions 
that are outside normal organizational procedures and that it make 
major changes in corporate management 
the retirement of philadelphia electric president john h austin 
jr was announced the same day last years letter was released 
philadelphia electric which operates the plant and the three 
other utilities that also own the plant announced last year they 
would share the burden of a record 125 million nrc fine 
inpo is an independent industry watchdog group composed of the 
utilities owning and operating nuclear plants it was formed in 1979 
after the accident at the three mile island reactor 
